title: For Sale:  Desert Tech HTI
postcontent:
This is a longer posting, but there is a lot of info.
 
 
Up for sale is my Desert Tech HTI in 50 BMG and with a 408 CheyTac Conversion, 60 rds of Hornady 50 BMG ammo and 20 rds of HSM 408 CheyTac ammo. It has an SWFA 10x42mm scope on it. I bought it with the 408 barrel installed and slightly used (10 rds to sight it in). When it arrived, I installed the 50 BMG barrel and didn’t shoot any 408 with it, so the 408 barrel is essentially brand new and not even broken in. I still have the box from Desert Tech with the papers in it, but the manual of arms they sent was for an SRS. However, the PDF for the HTI can be downloaded from Desert Tech’s website for free and is very clear.
 
 
Since I’ve owned it, I have put about 50 rounds of 50 BMG down range, with ZERO malfunctions. I clean it every 5-10 rounds, so the barrel is pristine and the action is smooth. This rifle is a tack-driver and is sighted in for 100 yds (yes this is short range for the rifle, but that’s the longest range I have available).
 
 
Please, no low-ball offers: this package is already an awesome deal at what I’m asking. To build this yourself would cost around $10,600 with glass and ammo, so at $9,000, I am not going to move on my price. I also will not split up the package and sell only one caliber with the chassis or sell you just the ammo: it’s an “all or nothing” deal.
 
 
I prefer to meet in person at an FFL to make the sale and transfer, and I will drive up to 2 hrs/75 miles from my location to another FFL to accommodate your needs. title: For Sale:  Sharps New Model 1863 Saddle Ring Cavalry Carbine
postcontent: This is a Sharps New Model 1863 Saddle Ring Cavalry Carbine from the Civil War era. The Sharps Carbine was the most widely issued and important Federal Civil War cavalry carbine. This New Model 1863 Carbine has a military blue barrel with an oil finished walnut stock and forearm. The barrel is fitted with a Lawrence patent folding leaf sight graduated to 800 yards. The straight breech receiver has the Sharps pellet priming system and a sling bar and ring on the left side. The top of the barrel has the three line Sharps address between the rear sight and barrel band, "NEW MODEL 1863" located between the rear sight and the receiver, which is also marked with E.A.W. inspectors mark. This rifle is still chambered in .52 caliber percussion, which is somewhat rare as many were converted to the cartridge postwar. The wood is in excellent condition with no major cracks or chips.

title: For Sale:  Steyr Scout Package .308
postcontent: Steyr Scout Package .308, BNIB.  Buy this rifle online at www.copsgunshop.net.  All FFL rules and regs apply.  Oklahoma residents pay state sales tax.  FREE SHIPPING! Sorry, no trades.   This package includes a .308 Win Scout mounted with Swarovski Z3 3-10x42 Optic 4A Reticle and Leupold Mounts. All colors include a 1/2x20 threaded barrel from the factory. The Steyr Scout provides the ideal solution for versatility, durability, accuracy and reliability in a compact and lightweight bolt-action rifle platform. Developed in a nearly decade-long collaboration with legendary Marine Corps Lt.Col. Jeff Cooper, the Scout boasts an extensive list of innovative features. The lightweight bolt-action, all-purpose Steyr Scout rifle was designed to accept a low-powered, forward-mounted scope for accurate fire and both-eyes-open operation to detect flanking dangers. Backup “ghost-ring” iron sights integrated to the top rail can be deployed within seconds should the optics fail. The rifle can also be fitted with a standard scope, should the need arise. In keeping with Cooper’s requirement for a magazine cutoff, Steyr incorporated a two-position magazine system that allowed the rifle to be fed individually with the five-round magazine in a lowered position. The magazine could be seated one step further with minimal pressure, allowing the bolt to feed cartridges directly from the magazine. A second five-round backup magazine is contained in the buttstock in case of an urgent need to reload. With a fluted, cold-hammer-forged barrel measuring 19 inches, an overall length of 38.6 inches and an out-of-the-box weight of just 6.6 pounds, the Scout is a breeze to pack out on long adventures, patrolling the farm or taking a quick trip to the range. The compact design of the stock features an innovative integrated bipod that is hardly noticeable until it is folded out from the stock. Between the bipod legs is a UIT rail for attachments, and the stock is outfitted with five press-and-twist sling-swivel attachment points that allow the addition of Cooper’s favored Ching Sling on either side of the rifle. The Steyr Scout is built on the Safe Bolt System (SBS) action with a unique 2+1 safety function that offers three settings operated by a wheel switch on the tang of the stock. The FIRE mode (safety off) is indicated by a red dot, and the first level of SAFE mode disables the firing mechanism while allowing the bolt to be cycled. The second SAFE position locks the bolt, at which point the bolt can be pushed down against the stock, locking the firing pin and firing mechanism out of firing position, allowing safe transportation with a round in the chamber. Simply pressing the safety’s release tab and rolling it forward returns the bolt to either the SAFE or the FIRE position. The Steyr Scout is available in a choice of Black, Grey, Mud and Green, and it is available chambered in .308 Winchester. Two 5-round magazines are included. A high-capacity conversion kit and hi-capacity magazines are also available to increase carry capacity to 20 rounds. The unique features make the Scout a self-contained platform that can easily be carried in a rifle scabbard without any need for attaching/detaching a bipod or finding extra pockets for a spare magazine, perfect for use on horseback, ATV or on a vehicle rifle rack.
